<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a JWT Generator?", answer: "A JWT Generator creates JSON Web Tokens by encoding a header and payload as Base64URL strings and signing them with a secret key using HMAC-SHA256. The resulting token has three parts separated by dots: header.payload.signature. This tool lets you specify custom headers, payloads, and secret keys to generate valid JWTs for testing and development." },
  { question: "How is a JWT signature created?", answer: "The JWT signature is created by Base64URL-encoding the header and payload separately, joining them with a dot, then computing an HMAC-SHA256 hash of that string using the secret key. The resulting hash is also Base64URL-encoded to form the third part of the token. This signature ensures the token has not been tampered with and was created by someone who knows the secret key." },
  { question: "Can I use this JWT in production?", answer: "This tool is designed for development and testing purposes. While the tokens it generates are technically valid JWTs with proper HMAC-SHA256 signatures, production tokens should be generated server-side using established libraries like ruby-jwt, jsonwebtoken (Node.js), or PyJWT (Python) that handle edge cases, key rotation, and security best practices." },
  { question: "What claims should I include in my JWT payload?", answer: "Common JWT claims include: sub (subject - user identifier), iss (issuer - your application), exp (expiration time as Unix timestamp), iat (issued at - current timestamp), aud (audience - intended recipient), and nbf (not before). You can also add custom claims like roles, permissions, or any application-specific data." },
  { question: "What is the difference between JWT Generator and JWT Decoder?", answer: "A JWT Generator creates new tokens by encoding header and payload data and signing them with a secret key. A JWT Decoder takes an existing token and extracts its header and payload by Base64-decoding them. The generator creates tokens; the decoder reads them. Both are essential tools for working with JWT-based authentication." }
]) %>

